C: when I was a fellow, they were doing their cases in Mexico, everyone said no, and they ended up with me. They said can you go to Mexico and I said sure. Did I tell you this?
N: no
C: I tell this story every year. There were 3 surgeons doing 13 surgeries in 8 days, so I was there in the or teaching these surgeons, and there was one who had lap experience, and he needed only a little coaching, but the other two were open, and a couple things made it hard. So when we ran out of instruments, we ran out of instruments, that was it. And I tried the American thing where you complain and you get what you want, and they were like no no no, so we were having to manually override the system so we could use expired instruments, we didn’t have rv situates and we had to use sh needles, out of that week and out of necessity, I had to get people out of cutting the prostate in half, cutting the gastric, all but the most major snafus… , upper gastric injury, it was a crash course of how to get people out of trouble, and so for each step I had to take them out of the console and walk them through it verbally, it was like the wild west, so that week I learned SO much.
N: I can imagine
C: so first I figured I could get people out of trouble, and I was explaining how to handle things. So that week was a crash course, and the best part of the end of the week, they called me into this room, and they handed me a paper bag full of cash, it wasn’t a lot, but to me and I was able to buy furniture for my nursery, I had just finished fellowship. I only found out later that the only reason I got that job because nobody else wanted to go down. But apparently one of the more famous guys came down.
What I learned from there, the instruments they matter, but it doesn’t really matter that much, you can get the job done a lot of different ways, it’s the strategy that matters, you just have to take a different approach. ***

st
, there are a couple of things that I normally won’t say. There’s a strong tendency for people to think, they have to know where the anatomy is at all times. That forces people to prematurely identify where things are, and when contradictory evidence comes out later on, they are too proud to change their minds. So it’s important to say “I think this is X, but I’m not sure, we’ll see.” But you should make guesses along the way, to help yourself along, but to yourself, you should be making guesses to yourself, if you’re wrong later, you can change. But if you just watch this like it’s a movie, but then the process is yup, yup, uh huh, yup. And then when it’s time for you to do the work, you missed, you missed the cases. Think to yourself, if it were me, I would go here next, and if I do something different, you ask yourself okay, why? That’s what active watching is, okay? So when you finally get called out of the dugout, you’ve done the hard work already, and you just have to learn how to use the robot, which is not the hard part to learn. Okay? ***
